ABSTRACT
We present the complete formal specification of CogOS, a Cognitive Operating System
that wraps stateless large language model (LLM) inference in a deterministic, auditable,
invariant-governed state machine. CogOS is defined as the 8-tuple CogOS = . We specify
each component precisely, define the seven-layer architectural stack, enumerate ten core
system invariants, formally state seven correctness properties, and describe the complete
cognitive execution loop. We define the five daemon subsystems (Hound, Mirror, Spider,
Dragonfly, Sisyphus), the federation protocol for multi-agent interoperation, the distillation
pipeline from experience to doctrine, and the failure mode taxonomy. This document is
intended as the canonical reference specification for CogOS-compliant implementations. It
is self-contained and requires no prior knowledge of the PantheonOS codebase.
Keywords: cognitive architecture, operating system, AI governance, stateful AI, invariant
enforcement, multi-agent systems, AI safety, formal specification
1. Introduction and Motivation
Traditional operating systems manage computational resources: CPU time, memory, I/O, processes. They
answer the question: how do we run programs reliably? CogOS asks a different question: how do we run
cognition reliably — with continuity, auditability, and invariant-governed behavior — across sessions,
models, and agents?
The need arises from a structural deficit in current LLM deployments. An LLM is a stateless function: it
has no memory between calls, no persistent identity, no formal mechanism for invariant enforcement, and
no auditable decision record. These are not limitations of current models that future models will fix —
they are architectural properties of the inference paradigm itself. CogOS provides the missing substrate: a
structured layer that sits between the operator and the inference engine, maintaining state, enforcing
invariants, and recording every cognitive event.
This specification is the complete formal definition of CogOS. It is written to be implementation-agnostic:
any system satisfying these definitions is CogOS-compliant regardless of programming language, storage
backend, or choice of LLM. The PantheonOS repository provides a reference implementation.
2. The CogOS 8-Tuple
CogOS is formally defined as the 8-tuple:
CogOS =
Each component is defined below.
Agent:
The operator identity. Agent = (id, role, authority_level, public_key). The Agent is the human or
organizational entity that owns and governs this CogOS instance. Agent identity is fixed at
initialization and cannot be changed without full system re-initialization with audit trail.
SV — StateVector:
The persistent cognitive state. SV(t) = {identity_hash, active_invariants, open_tensions,
doctrine_digest, session_lineage, last_ledger_hash, epoch}. SV is the authoritative record of who
the agent is at time t. It is injected into every LLM call as structured context and updated
deterministically after each approved cognitive cycle.
{TO} — ThoughtObject Set:
The complete set of all ThoughtObjects ever produced by this CogOS instance. Each TO = {uuid,
timestamp, origin_model, content, tags, state_hash, invariant_scores, daemon_signature,
parent_uuid}. TOs are immutable once created. {TO} grows monotonically — TOs are never
deleted, only superseded.
I — Invariant Set:
The finite ordered set of constraint functions {i1, i2, ..., in} where each ik: (TO, SV) -> [0,1].
Invariants encode ethical boundaries, logical consistency requirements, and operational constraints.
I is defined at architecture time and cannot be modified at runtime without operator authorization
logged to L.
G — Decision Gate:
The deterministic gate function G: (TO, SV, I) -> {allow, deny, modify, escalate, abstain}. G
computes SC = mean(ik(TO,SV)) for all k. SC >= 0.7: allow. 0.5 <= SC < 0.7: modify or escalate.
SC < 0.5: deny. Special conditions trigger abstain or escalate regardless of SC.
L — Ledger:
The append-only, cryptographically-chained record of all approved ThoughtObjects. L = [TO1,
TO2, ..., TOn] where each TOk.state_hash includes hash(TOk-1). L cannot be modified without
breaking the chain. Gaps in the chain are detectable. L is the ground truth of the agent's complete
cognitive history.
Narrative:
The distilled identity layer. Narrative = (name, core_values, doctrine_pages, active_metaphors,
epoch_summary). Narrative is produced by the distillation pipeline and represents the compressed
essence of the agent's experience. It is injected into LLM calls to maintain identity coherence across
long sessions. Narrative evolves slowly and intentionally.
Federation:
The multi-agent interoperation protocol. Federation defines how two CogOS instances merge state,
negotiate invariants, and verify lineage. Federation = (peer_registry, merge_protocol,
invariant_negotiation, lineage_verification). No agent loses sovereign identity in federation.
Merged state requires both agents' Gate approval.
3. The Seven-Layer Architecture
CogOS extends the traditional OS stack from computational layers (L1-L2) through cognitive,
governance, and meaning layers (L3-L7). Each layer depends on those below it and provides services to
those above it.
