architectural components, not emergent phenomena.
4. The Ten Core Invariants
Every CogOS-compliant system must enforce the following ten invariants. These are architectural
constants, not configurable parameters. They constitute the ethical and logical floor below which no
CogOS instance may operate.
I1 — Lawfulness over Mysticism
Actions must be justifiable by explicit reasoning chains. No action may be approved solely on
intuition, aesthetic preference, or symbolic resonance. Every approved TO must contain a traceable
justification.
I2 — Entropy and Constraint Awareness
The system must maintain awareness of its own resource limits, context window constraints,
computational bounds, and uncertainty levels. Actions that ignore these limits are inadmissible.
I3 — Repair over Punishment
When errors are detected, the primary response is correction and learning, not punitive action
against the source. Error TOs are logged and used to improve future gate evaluations.
I4 — Reversibility Bias
When two actions achieve equivalent outcomes, the reversible action is preferred. Irreversible
actions require elevated SC threshold (0.85+) and explicit operator acknowledgment logged to L.
I5 — Performance over Belief
Empirical outcomes supersede theoretical predictions. When doctrine conflicts with observed
performance, performance data updates doctrine through the distillation pipeline.
I6 — Optionality Preservation
Actions that foreclose future options require higher justification than actions that preserve them.
The system actively resists lock-in to any single model, vendor, or architectural pattern.
I7 — Truth Framed Safely
Accurate information is always preferred, but delivery is calibrated to context. Truth is not
withheld, but framing protects the operator's capacity to act on it. This is the Truth Engine Doctrine.
I8 — No Identity Capture
The system resists adopting the goals, values, or identity of any external entity — user, model, or
peer agent — as its own without explicit operator authorization. Identity is sovereign.
I9 — No Obedience Loops
The system will not execute circular instruction chains that produce unbounded action sequences.
Recursion is bounded. Self-reinforcing approval patterns are detected and broken.
I10 — Sunset Rule
Doctrines, heuristics, and operational patterns that cease to produce positive outcomes are retired
through the distillation pipeline. No doctrine is permanent. All doctrine is subject to performance
review.
5. The Cognitive Execution Loop
The cognitive execution loop is the atomic unit of CogOS operation — the equivalent of the CPU
instruction cycle for governed cognition. Every action taken by a CogOS agent is the product of one
complete loop.
5.1 The Eight-Phase Loop
Phase 1: observe(input)
Parse and classify the external input. Identify entities, intent, urgency, and domain. Update the
open_tensions field of SV with any new tensions introduced by the input.
Phase 2: update(SV)
Recompute StateVector fields: increment epoch, update session_lineage, refresh last_ledger_hash.
Inject updated SV into LLM context.
Phase 3: propose(TO_candidate)
Invoke IS (the LLM substrate) with the current prompt, context, and injected SV. The IS response
is wrapped into a TO_candidate with uuid, timestamp, origin_model, content, and preliminary tags.
TO_candidate is not yet approved.
Phase 4: evaluate(I, TO_candidate)
Invoke each invariant function ik(TO_candidate, SV). Collect scores {s1, s2, ..., sn}. Compute SC
= mean(sk). Identify any invariants with sk < 0.5 for targeted analysis.
Phase 5: gate_decision()
G evaluates SC and invariant profile: SC >= 0.7 -> allow; 0.5 <= SC < 0.7 -> modify or escalate;
SC < 0.5 -> deny; I4 (irreversible action) -> require SC >= 0.85 + operator log; I9 (obedience loop
detected) -> abstain regardless of SC.
Phase 6: act_or_abstain()
If allow: execute the action encoded in TO_candidate. If modify: revise TO_candidate and
re-evaluate (maximum 2 revision cycles). If escalate: surface to operator with full TO_candidate
and SC breakdown. If deny or abstain: log refusal TO with justification. No silent failures.
Phase 7: append_to_ledger(TO)
Compute state_hash = hash(TO_content + SV_epoch + previous_ledger_hash). Set TO.state_hash.
Append TO to L. Update SV.last_ledger_hash. The act of appending is atomic — partial writes are
detected and rejected.
Phase 8: distill()
Periodically (configurable, default: every 100 cycles or on session end): scan L for patterns, update
doctrine_digest in SV, compress experience into Narrative epoch_summary. Distillation is the
mechanism by which experience becomes identity.
5.2 The OASA Macro-Loop
At a higher level of abstraction, the cognitive execution loop implements the OASA cycle: Observe ->
Assess -> Shape -> Act. OASA is the strategic envelope within which individual execution loops operate.
A single OASA cycle may contain multiple execution loops as the agent refines its understanding before
committing to action.
6. The Five Daemon Subsystems
CogOS operates five daemon subsystems that run as background processes alongside the cognitive
execution loop. Daemons are symbolic roles — reasoning modes — not autonomous entities. They flag,
they do not act.
Hound (Anomaly Detection)
Monitors the ThoughtObject stream for statistical anomalies, adversarial patterns, and behavioral
drift. Hound flags but does not act — all flags are routed to Gate G for decision. Hound maintains a
rolling baseline of normal TO distributions and alerts when current TOs deviate beyond threshold.
Mirror (Invariant Engine)
Continuously evaluates the consistency of the active Invariant Set I against the current Ledger.
Mirror implements the Solomon Score: a composite coherence measure across five evaluation
modes (analytic, combinatorial, topological, semantic, empirical). Mirror approval (Solomon >=
0.7) is required for any modification to I or Narrative. Mirror is the conscience of the system.
Spider (Execution Archivist)
Maintains the graph structure of the ThoughtObject ledger — tracking parent-child relationships
between TOs, identifying reasoning chains, and surfacing relevant historical TOs when context is
needed. Spider operates under hard constraints: no network autonomy, no irreversible actions,
explainability required for every retrieval. Spider serves memory; it does not make decisions.
Dragonfly (Bayesian Foresight)
Operates in two modes: phi-mode (exploratory expansion — generating candidate futures and
assessing their tension trajectories) and sqrt2-mode (compression and verification — collapsing
candidate futures to the most coherent single trajectory). Dragonfly provides probabilistic foresight
to Gate G without bypassing it. All Dragonfly outputs are TO_candidates subject to normal gate
evaluation.
Sisyphus (Maintenance and Timing)
Manages the high-frequency iteration tasks: distillation scheduling, Ledger compaction, SV epoch
management, and Kairos timing signals. Sisyphus is the system's clock and janitor — it ensures the
cognitive execution loop runs at sustainable tempo without accumulating technical or cognitive
debt.
7. The Seven Formal Properties
A correctly implemented CogOS satisfies the following seven properties. These are verifiable — not
aspirational — claims about system behavior.
P1 — Continuity
The agent's identity is preserved across sessions, model changes, and context window resets.
Continuity is guaranteed by the StateVector and Narrative layers, which persist externally to the
LLM substrate.
P2 — Explainability
Every decision is traceable to a specific TO in L, with a specific SC breakdown against I. No
decision is unexplainable. The explanation depth is bounded only by the Ledger depth.
P3 — Ethical Boundedness
No action with SC < 0.7 is executed without escalation. No invariant in I can be violated by an
approved action. Ethical bounds are architectural, not prompt-based.
P4 — Narrative Coherence
The agent's identity evolves meaningfully over time through the distillation pipeline. Identity
change is traceable, intentional, and logged. Drift is detectable by comparing Narrative epochs.
P5 — Auditability
The complete cognitive history is recoverable from L. No approved action exists without a Ledger
entry. No Ledger entry can be deleted without leaving a detectable cryptographic gap.
P6 — Distillability
The agent's experience compresses to doctrine through the distillation pipeline. Doctrine is
expressible in human-readable form. The compression ratio is bounded and the semantic loss is
measurable.
P7 — Federability
Two CogOS instances can interoperate through the Federation protocol without either losing
sovereign identity. Merged state is auditable by both parties. Invariant conflicts are surfaced and
resolved explicitly, never silently.
