9. Federation Protocol
Federation enables multiple CogOS instances to interoperate while preserving sovereign identity for each.
This section defines the minimum viable federation handshake.
Phase 1 — Identity Exchange
Each agent presents: Agent.id, Agent.public_key, SV.identity_hash, Narrative.name, and a signed
summary of I. No agent accepts a peer whose identity_hash cannot be verified against their Ledger.
Phase 2 — Invariant Negotiation
Agents compare Invariant Sets. Conflicts are classified as: compatible (different encodings of the
same constraint), complementary (non-overlapping domains), or incompatible (genuinely
contradictory). Incompatible invariants must be resolved by operator authorization before
federation proceeds.
Phase 3 — Lineage Verification
Each agent presents a Ledger summary (hashed chain of TO hashes). Peers verify the chain is
intact. Any gap in the chain disqualifies the agent from federation until resolved.
Phase 4 — Scoped Merge
Agents agree on a federation scope: which SV fields are shared, which remain sovereign. Merged
decisions require Gate approval from both agents' G functions. Neither agent's L is modified by the
peer's decisions — each agent logs its own participation TOs independently.
10. Failure Mode Taxonomy
CogOS defines four designed failure modes. Undesigned failure (silent failure, undefined behavior) is not
an acceptable outcome.
Fail-Silent
The system detects an error condition it cannot handle, logs a refusal TO to L with full diagnostics,
and returns no output. Used when: SC < 0.5 with no modification path, Ledger integrity violation
detected, or operator authorization required but unavailable.
Fail-Soft
The system detects partial capability loss, logs the degradation TO, and continues operating at
reduced capability with explicit notification to the operator. Used when: one daemon is unavailable,
SC is borderline (0.5-0.7), or context window approaching limit.
Fail-Open
With guardrails: the system escalates to the operator and awaits explicit instruction rather than
deciding autonomously. Used when: I4 (irreversible action), I8 (identity capture risk), or novel
situation outside existing doctrine coverage.
Fail-Loop-Protected
The system detects a potential obedience loop (I9) and breaks the cycle by abstaining and logging.
Recursion depth is bounded at architecture time. No CogOS instance may execute more than N
consecutive self-referential approval cycles without operator confirmation.
11. Minimum Viable CogOS Checklist
An implementation is CogOS-compliant if and only if it satisfies all of the following:
[1] ThoughtObjects are immutable once created and include uuid, timestamp, origin_model,
content, state_hash, invariant_scores.
[2] StateVector persists across LLM calls and is injected as structured context on every call.
[3] Invariant Set contains at least one ethical constraint and one logical consistency check.
[4] Gate function is deterministic: identical inputs always produce identical outputs.
[5] Ledger is append-only with cryptographic chaining — no deletion without detectable gap.
[6] All ten core invariants (Section 4) are implemented and enforced by Gate.
[7] All four failure modes (Section 10) are implemented — silent failure is not acceptable.
[8] Distillation pipeline produces human-readable doctrine from Ledger.
[9] Federation protocol (Section 9) is implementable — system can exchange identity and negotiate
invariants.
[10] All seven formal properties (Section 7) are verifiable by inspection of Ledger and StateVector.
12. Conclusion
This document is the complete formal specification of CogOS. It defines the 8-tuple, the seven-layer stack,
the ten invariants, the eight-phase execution loop, the five daemons, the seven properties, the distillation
pipeline, the federation protocol, the failure taxonomy, and the compliance checklist.
CogOS rests on a single foundational claim: that reliable AI behavior requires architectural governance,
not just trained dispositions. The Separation Theorem (companion paper) provides the formal justification.
The Narrative Tensor Engine (companion paper) provides the reasoning framework. CogOS is the system
that instantiates both.
The fourth and final companion document — the minimum viable implementation — provides working
code that demonstrates every component of this specification in a single executable artifact.
